{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653404"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:46:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:46:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18571"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18571"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11303"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114154"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11303"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18571"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96154"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10291"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26208"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26210"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114154"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAction potentials travel rapidly along myelinated axons in the nervous system, allowing efficient signal transmission.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how myelin increases action potential conduction velocity?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amplifies the action potential magnitude","Reduces membrane resistance and capacitance","Increases sodium ion concentration inside the axon","Provides continuous conduction along the axon","Increases the number of voltage-gated channels"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces membrane resistance and capacitance\u003C/strong\u003E is correct because myelin acts as an electrical insulator that prevents ion leakage and reduces the capacitive load on the axon membrane. This allows the action potential to jump from node to node (saltatory conduction), greatly increasing conduction velocity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmplifies the action potential magnitude\u003C/strong\u003E does not occur as action potential amplitude remains constant regardless of myelination. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases sodium ion concentration inside the axon\u003C/strong\u003E is not a function of myelin, which does not affect intracellular ion concentrations. \u003Cstrong\u003EProvides continuous conduction along the axon\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect since myelinated axons actually conduct via saltatory conduction between nodes rather than continuously. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases the number of voltage-gated channels\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect as myelin reduces channel density except at nodes of Ranvier.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe increased conduction velocity in myelinated axons results from both electrical insulation and the clustering of voltage-gated sodium channels at the nodes of Ranvier, allowing the action potential to jump efficiently between nodes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Action potentials propagate along myelinated axons via saltatory conduction, jumping between nodes of Ranvier.","Myelin increases conduction velocity by preventing ion leakage and reducing membrane capacitance.","Voltage-gated sodium channels are concentrated at nodes of Ranvier in myelinated axons."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall 